[{"id":"VH912414-22","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Read each question carefully. Write your response in the space provided for each part of each question. Answers must be written out in paragraph form. Outlines, bulleted lists, or diagrams alone are not acceptable and will not be scored.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The diagram shows water molecules as solid ice at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0 degrees Celsius\"><math alttext=\"0 degrees Celsius\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>°</mi><mstyle mathvariant=\"normal\"><mi>C</mi></mstyle></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and as a liquid at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"25 degrees Celsius\"><math alttext=\"25 degrees Celsius\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle mathvariant=\"normal\"><mrow><mn>25</mn><mi>°</mi><mi>C</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two diagrams. Each diagram consists of water molecules. The first diagram is labeled Ice. In this diagram, each water molecule is bonded to two other water molecules. The water molecules create adjacent hexagonal shapes. The second diagram is labeled Liquid Water. In this diagram several of the water molecules are bonded to two other water molecules, some are bonded to one other water molecule, and some water molecules are unbonded.\" height=\"216\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH912414.g02.png\" width=\"400\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:a part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"a\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Describe</span> why hydrogen bonds form between water molecules.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VH912414-22","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:b part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"b\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Explain</span> why the arrangement of water molecules is different in ice and water.</p></div>\n"},{"id":"VH912414-22","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:c part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"c\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) To help explain surface tension, use a single water molecule in the template and <span class=\"font_weight:bold formatted_text\">draw</span> arrows representing the possible locations of hydrogen bonds formed by the molecule. The possible hydrogen bonds formed by a water molecule below the surface are shown.</p>\n\n<p class=\"standalone_statement style:1\">Template for Part (c)</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram that consists of circles that are somewhat tightly packed in a box. Each circle represents a Water Molecule. The top layer of circles represents the Surface of Water. Five arrows extend from one of the circles near the middle of the box.\" height=\"217\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH912414.g03.png\" width=\"400\" /></div>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VH912414-22","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:d part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"d\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) The arrangement of the water molecules in ice causes the ice to float. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Explain</span> how ice floating on the surface of a body of water affects the water in a way that is beneficial to the organisms in it.</p></div>\n"}]